{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492591"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1108"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1108"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.55,0.07,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1108"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89362"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"640"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4258"},{"type":"tags","id":"4264"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44497"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of increasing left-sided abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and she has never experienced anything like this before. Prolonged application of hot water bottle gave her some initial relief. Her history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension. She reports a penicillin allergy causing nausea and vomiting, but denies any other allergies. Three days ago she saw her general practitioner about a chest infection and was started on a course of antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 112/74 mmHg, pulse 94/min and temperature 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The following view of her abdomen is seen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the physical sign demonstrated in the image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug allergy","Bullous insect bite reaction","Thermal burn","Herpes zoster","Toxic epidermal necrolysis from antibiotic administration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows that an appropriate examination of the abdomen is being performed, with adequate exposure from the groins up to the xiphisternum. The diagnosis is evident from the history of prolonged heat being applied to the area from which the pain arose. The lesion pictured is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethermal burn\u003C/strong\u003E or heat blister with an associated heat rash (note the surrounding erythema extending some way from the lesion), in which the epidermis has separated from the dermis and injury-associated capillary leakage has caused fluid to accumulate between the layers. Her history is notable for severe abdominal pain in which an attempted treatment was a hot water bottle was applied to her abdomen - (in this real case this information was only provided once the abdomen was being examined). In this case the burn is not the underlying cause of her presentation but rather a manifestation of her attempt to treat her pain. The cause of the abdominal pain in this case is still undifferentiated and would require further evaluation depending on the remainder of the examination findings and relevant investigations, however this is not the focus of this question. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug allergy rash\u003C/strong\u003E tends to present as a erythematous rash that can be macropapular in nature, and appears more generalised rather than the localised lesion seen here. In this patient, given she has a known history of penicillin allergy, it is unlikely she would be prescribed or take a penicillin-based antibiotic. Even with her history of penicillin allergy, this is unlikely diagnosis even if she was prescribed penicillin-like antibiotics as previous reactions suggest a gastrointestinal intolerance, rather than a cutaneous reaction. Moreover, drug allergies are unlikely to blister, except in cases of bullous fixed drug eruption, Steven-Johnson syndrome (SJN) or \u003Cstrong\u003Etoxic epidermal necrolysis\u003C/strong\u003E (TEN) - important diagnoses that need to be excluded. SJN presents with \u0026lt;10% of total skin detachment, whilst TEN presents with \u0026gt;30% skin detachment. However, the patient does not obviously have \u0026gt;30% skin detachment, making TEN the incorrect answer option. In the case of bullous fixed drug eruptions, they are extremely rare and tend to have a more purple colour and have a prodromal single patch of plaque that will then ulcerate - all of which is inconsistent with the history and image above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebullous insect bite reaction\u003C/strong\u003E can present in a similar way to the lesion seen above, and is an important differential especially in those with a previous history of reactions or allergy to bites. Saliva from the insect is often thought to be trigger. However, truncal bites are less common than extremity bites due to lower skin exposure, and the presence of surrounding erythema extending some way from the blister makes a different reaction more likely than a bite reaction in this patient as bite reactions present more locally without much surrounding erythema. Moreover, insect bites tend to have a \u0022breakfast, lunch and dinner\u0022 sign which refers to an insect taking multiple bites in a line in a localized area - which this patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely cause of the rash seen above. It tends to present in a dermatomal distrubution of vesicles, often with a preceeding flu-like illness. Given this patient has a single blister and no vesicles, as well as a non-dermatomal distribution of the rash and blister, this is an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heat blisters are an easily avoidable iatrogenic injury","TEN and SJS are serious differential diagnoses that need to be ruled out"],"references":["Gupta S, Chittoria RK, Chavan V, et al. Role of Burn Blister Fluid in Wound Healing. J Cutan Aesthet Surg. 2021;14(3):370-373. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34908785/","Ngan V. Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome [Internet]. DermNet. 2009 [cited 2023Apr7]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/staphylococcal-scalded-skin-syndrome","Collins P, Sepede J. Bullous arthropod bite reaction. BMJ Case Reports. 2018;11(1).","Nair PA, Patel BC. Herpes Zoster. [Updated 2022 Sep 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441824/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1108"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20947"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20947"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/POEM4snOuSXjqmf8DrW2NEwckSttQe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/POEM4snOuSXjqmf8DrW2NEwckSttQe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":646,"height":572}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T18:28:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T18:30:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1108"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106876"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u